I&#x27;ve tried to use and get comfortable with Powershell but it&#x27;s insistence on types and overly heavy syntax just get in the way for my primary use case for shell scripting. (e.g. quick and dirty hacks)<p>I don&#x27;t in fact get tired of unstructured data and the limitations of the shell like basic data structures because nine times out of 10 the data I have to work with in a shell is exactly that. Unstructured and basic. Not because of the shell but because the source of that data provides it that way.<p>Powershell with it&#x27;s intense focus on fancy datastructures makes something like<p><pre><code>    sed &#x27;/foo/d&#x27;
</code></pre>
unecessarily hard and that&#x27;s exactly the sort of thing I use my shell for.<p>If I want something more powerful for working with structured data I&#x27;ll use Python or Julia.
